"Pours a clear, copper color. 2/3 inch head of an off-white color. Great retention and great lacing. Smells of citrus hops, hint of earthy malt, sweet malt, caramel malt, hint of pale malt, and a hint of biscuit. Fits the style of an extra special / strong bitter. Mouth feel is smooth and cream, with a low carbonation level. Tastes of sweet malt, caramel malt, citrus hops, hint of pale malt, hint of yeast, and a hint of biscuit. Overall, great appearance, good aroma, body, and blend."
""
""
""
""
"i like that left hand has started putting these beers out on nitro, although im not sure its as good as a real nitro tap. in fact, its definitely not. while the beer looks really nice, the liquid itself is rather flat after all the little nitro bubbles come out. clear copper color, whipped cream head. the nose is a little more malty than i remember sawtooth being. in fact, its got an almost metallic vibe, but its not at all unpleasant. english ale yeast breaks down most of the sweetness, and a very clean and clear beer results, very autumnal in nature, with a hearty body and flavors of fresh grain and faint cider. i prefer the non-nitro edition and here is why. sawtooth is made by its feel, and that lively carbonation is has is missed here. the smoother but stiller nitro makes it more like a classic esb, but the regular version is more intriguing to me, keenly skirting style guidelines in favor of an attention holding session ale. this is a little more generic despite the format. still a worthwhile endeavor."
""
